04757nam a22007815i 9781442689015DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426890157 a10.3138/97814426890152doi  a(DE-B1597)465351  a(OCoLC)1013966719  a(OCoLC)944176663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ4053.T75bB59 2008eb 7aLIT0042002bisacsh04a850.9/9287090451 aBlum, Cinzia Sartini, eauthor.10aRewriting the Journey in Contemporary Italian Literature :bFigures of Subjectivity in Progress /cCinzia Sartini Blum. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Beyond the End of the Journey -- tChapter 2. Gradiva's Journey: Genealogy of a Feminist Trope -- tChapter 3. Biancamaria Frabotta's Lead: From fuga to viandanza -- tChapter 4. Walking in the Shoes of Another: Dacia Maraini's Departures and Returns -- tChapter 5. Exile as the Ultimate Utopia: Toni Maraini's vivere vagabondo -- tChapter 6. Bridging Cultures: Figures of Mediation -- tConclusion: Toward an Interactive Universalism -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe mobility of women is a central issue in feminist analysis of literary works and historical periods. Rewriting the Journey in Contemporary Italian Literature explores the concept of the journey from feminist, psychoanalytic, and postcolonial perspectives, in order to offer an alternative understanding of "moving." Cinzia Sartini Blum examines the new literature of migration in Italian and journeys in the works of Biancamaria Frabotta, Dacia Maraini, Toni Maraini, and Maria Pace Ottieri, to demonstrate that women writers and migrant authors in contemporary Italy present journeys as events that are beyond heroic modern exploration and postmodern fragmentation.Using the mythical figure of Gradiva, Blum shows how contemporary Italian women writers have reinvented Gradiva to reveal subjectivities that challenge and overcome the postmodern melancholia and nihilism prevalent in contemporary male writers and thinkers. She also considers the connection between metaphorical and literal mobility, the role of the intellectual as cultural intermediary, the roles of women in cultural encounters within mass migrations, and how migrancy is a way of being in the postcolonial world.An impeccable piece of original scholarship, Rewriting the Journey in Contemporary Italian Literature will be of interest to feminist, literary, and postcolonial scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aDisplacement (Psychology) in literature. 0aEmigration and immigration in literature. 0aItalian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aItalian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442689015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442689015.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG